+## Syntax-Failure Recovery Requirements
 
-`python3 ppd/tests/validate_ppd.py`
+When recent daemon failures include `SyntaxError`, `py_compile`, `TS1005`, `TS1109`, or `TS1128`, the next retry must use the smallest file set that can make progress. Prefer a single replacement file with explicit syntactic-validity guardrails over multi-file refactors.
+
+A failed syntax preflight should be classified as `syntax_preflight`, rolled back immediately, and summarized with compact diagnostics. The daemon should avoid running the full unittest suite after a parser failure because the parser error is already the blocking signal.
+
+## Task Selection Requirements
+
+The supervisor should select tasks in this order:
+
+1. Unblocked validation or fixture tasks that operate only on committed fixtures.
+2. Narrow daemon repair tasks that improve preflight, retry guidance, diagnostics, or task selection.
+3. Public dry-run work only after fixture validators pass.
+4. Authenticated DevHub automation only after explicit user authorization and after public fixture-first work is complete.
+
+The supervisor must not select tasks that would create private DevHub session files, authentication state, traces, raw crawl output, downloaded documents, CAPTCHA/MFA automation, payment actions, submissions, certifications, cancellations, official uploads, or inspection scheduling.
+
+## Planning New Work
+
+If all remaining selectable tasks are stale or blocked, append a new unchecked task to `ppd/daemon/task-board.md` rather than modifying completed tasks. New tasks must be narrow enough for one daemon cycle and should prefer fixture-first or validation-first work before live or authenticated automation.
+
+A suitable next task after the public-crawl dry-run fixture validator has passed is a daemon task that records stale-block supersession in supervisor diagnostics or task selection, without editing crawler fixtures or PP&D domain code.
